</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,801,1069]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Erichson" authorityYear="1835" box="[160,425,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Scatonomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciculatus">
<emphasis box="[160,425,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Scatonomus fasciculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1835" box="[479,600,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Scatonomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatus">
<emphasis box="[479,600,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">S. barbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are closely related. Both species have body longer than 
<quantity box="[223,296,871,896]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097" unit="mm" value="9.0">9 mm</quantity>
; dorsal surface shiny, almost smooth; genal edge not distinctly angulate laterally (
<figureCitation box="[267,363,906,931]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[171,1141,146,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[163,1153,142,1262]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Head, dorsal view. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov. (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020909/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(a, d)); and clypeal edge bidentate, with deep lateral emarginations filled with a tuft of long setae (
<figureCitation box="[496,586,940,965]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[171,1141,146,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[163,1153,142,1262]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Head, dorsal view. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov. (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020909/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(a, d)). However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Erichson" authorityYear="1835" box="[769,919,940,965]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Scatonomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciculatus">
<emphasis box="[769,919,940,965]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">S. fasciculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the following combination of characters: clypeal median teeth elongated, approximately as long as the lateral tuft of setae (
<figureCitation box="[662,758,1010,1035]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[171,1141,146,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[163,1153,142,1262]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Head, dorsal view. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov. (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020909/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(d)); anterior edge of gena slightly straight (
<figureCitation box="[261,354,1044,1069]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[171,1141,146,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[163,1153,142,1262]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Head, dorsal view. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov. (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020909/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(d), arrow); and dorsum with blue or purple reflections (
<figureCitation box="[982,1070,1044,1069]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1145,1168]" captionTargetBox="[194,1153,143,1113]" captionTargetId="figure-187@5.[163,1153,142,1113]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Dorsal habitus. (a) S Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov.; (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020905" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020905/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(d)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="1098" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,1114,1728]" box="[160,320,1114,1138]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,320,1114,1138]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Redescription</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1156,1114,1728]" lastBlockId="18.[160,1156,142,549]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="1098" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,218,1149,1174]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Male</emphasis>
: length: 
<quantity box="[314,422,1149,1174]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="9.0">9–13 mm</quantity>
. Dorsum with black, blue or purple reflections (
<figureCitation box="[947,1034,1149,1174]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1145,1168]" captionTargetBox="[194,1153,143,1113]" captionTargetId="figure-187@5.[163,1153,142,1113]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Dorsal habitus. (a) S Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov.; (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020905" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020905/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(d)). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1087,1149,1149,1174]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Head</emphasis>
: densely punctate, slightly wrinkled medially (
<figureCitation box="[678,773,1183,1208]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[171,1141,146,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[163,1153,142,1262]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Head, dorsal view. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov. (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020909/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(d)). Anterior and posterior edges narrowly margined. Clypeo-genal and clypeo-frontal sutures carinate, arched. Clypeal median teeth upturned, separated by U-shaped emargination (
<figureCitation box="[910,1009,1253,1278]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1294,1317]" captionTargetBox="[171,1141,146,1237]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[163,1153,142,1262]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Head, dorsal view. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. canhedoae sp. nov. (holotype); (c) S. chalybaeus; (d) S. fasciculatus; (e) S. foresti sp. nov. (holotype); (f) S. insignis; (g) S. janssensi; (h) S. mitzae sp. nov. (holotype); (i) S. paulosawayai (holotype); (j, k) S. thalassinus; (l) S. viridis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020909" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020909/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(d)). Anterior portion of clypeus strongly concave medially, surface less punctate than remaining portions of head. Clypeal and genal edges with rows of long erect setae. Antennal club globose, densely coated with long setae. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[630,714,1357,1382]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Thorax</emphasis>
: pronotum shiny, puncticulate, slightly wrinkled. Anteromedian portion of pronotal disc longitudinally wrinkled, and with welldefined microgranulation. Mid-longitudinal sulcus feebly impressed on pronotal disc. Transverse carina of hypomera almost complete, not reaching lateral edge. Anterior portion of hypomera with dense long setae; lateral edge with row of coarse setose punctures, setae short. Surface of mesepimeron filled with dense and fine striae. Surface of mesanepisternum with well-defined microgranulation. Anterior and lateral lobes of metaventrite with well-defined microgranulation, lacking shallow punctures. Disc flat, densely puncticulate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[406,476,1634,1659]" pageId="17" pageNumber="1097">Elytra</emphasis>
: striae thin, shallow, indistinctly punctate; width of striae on disc 7 times narrower than the third interstria. Seventh and eighth striae effaced or absent at elytral base. Ninth stria present, weakly impressed at elytral base. Tenth stria inconspicuous. Interstriae plane, shiny, densely punctate, slightly wrinkled. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1098">Legs [ventral surface]</emphasis>
: profemora densely punctate, surface between punctures smooth. Mesofemora and metafemor sparsely punctate. Outer edge of protibia with 3 distinct teeth separated by deep U-shaped emarginations. Outer edge of mesotibiae and metatibiae with row of short setae and small teeth. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[476,593,281,306]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1098">Abdomen</emphasis>
: posterior half of abdominal ventrites II–VI convex at transverse midline. Ventrite V slightly depressed medially, as long as ventrite VI. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,274,350,375]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1098">Pygidium</emphasis>
: 1/3 wider than long. Surface shiny, with punctures spaced by 2 times their diameter. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[272,455,385,410]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1098">Genital capsule</emphasis>
: paramera apex divided into apical and lateral lobes by deep Lshaped emargination. Apical lobe rounded; lateral lobe slightly acute (
<figureCitation box="[1016,1115,420,445]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1191,1214]" captionTargetBox="[224,1152,142,1131]" captionTargetId="figure-205@9.[163,1153,142,1159]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 5. Aedeagus, detail of right paramera and endophallic sclerites. (a) Scatonomus barbatus stat. rev.; (b) S. chalybaeus; (c) S. fasciculatus; (d) S. foresti sp. nov.; (e) S. insignis; (f) S. janssensi; (g) S. mitzae sp. nov.; (h) S. thalassinus; (i) S. viridis; (j) endophallic sclerites of S. fasciculatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5020913" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5020913/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1098">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(c)). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,247,454,479]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1098">Female</emphasis>
: differs from male by the abdominal ventrite VI twice longer than V. Disc of pygidium with punctures spaced by 2 times their diameter; apical edge of pygidium slightly angulate.
</paragraph>
